WEBVTT

00:03.044 --> 00:05.922
<i>♪ The Simpsons ♪</i>

00:15.140 --> 00:19.060
-(chalk screeches)
-(bell rings)

00:23.565 --> 00:25.525
(work whistle blows)

00:28.278 --> 00:30.905
-(sucking)
-(register beeping)

00:39.080 --> 00:43.334
(jazzy solo)

00:46.463 --> 00:47.422
(tires screech)

00:53.553 --> 00:55.096
(tires screeching)

00:58.516 --> 00:59.809
(horn honks)

01:01.186 --> 01:02.187
(tires screech)

01:05.440 --> 01:07.650
-Aah!
-(tires screech)

01:10.445 --> 01:11.905
HOMER: D'oh!

01:21.873 --> 01:23.291
-MRS. KRABAPPEL: Bart.
-BART: Huh?

01:23.374 --> 01:24.334
MRS. KRABAPPEL: There will be
no further interruptions

01:24.417 --> 01:25.627
during Martin's book report.

01:25.710 --> 01:27.754
MARTIN:
"You're killing me, fish.

01:27.837 --> 01:29.297
"Never have I seen

01:29.380 --> 01:32.133
"a greater or more noble
thing than you, brother.

01:32.217 --> 01:33.760
"Come on and kill me.

01:33.843 --> 01:36.846
"I do not care
who kills who.

01:36.930 --> 01:38.306
"To catch a fish.

01:38.389 --> 01:40.058
"To kill a bull.

01:40.141 --> 01:42.060
"To make love to a woman.

01:42.936 --> 01:45.230
To live."

01:45.313 --> 01:46.689
I thank you.

01:46.773 --> 01:49.359
Oh, absolutely brilliant!

01:49.442 --> 01:51.861
There were moments
I truly believed

01:51.945 --> 01:53.988
you were Hemingway.
Bravo, Martin.

01:54.072 --> 01:55.865
Oh, please,
call me Papa.

01:55.949 --> 01:57.909
A little ketchup
for your buns, Papa?

01:57.992 --> 01:59.202
-Ooh!
-All right, class, all right.

01:59.285 --> 02:01.079
I think we have time
for one more report.

02:01.162 --> 02:02.622
-Bart Simpson?
-Oh!

02:02.705 --> 02:05.333
Is your book report on
"Treasure Island" ready?

02:05.416 --> 02:08.419
Is it ready?
Ha! What a question.

02:08.503 --> 02:11.047
Fellow students,
prepare to be dazzled.

02:11.131 --> 02:13.883
Well, as Mrs. Krabappel
already mentioned

02:13.967 --> 02:17.011
the name of the book that
I read was "Treasure Island."

02:17.095 --> 02:19.389
It's about these... pirates.

02:19.472 --> 02:22.809
Pirates with patches
over their eyes...

02:22.892 --> 02:24.435
and shiny gold teeth...

02:24.519 --> 02:27.397
and green birds
on their shoulders.

02:28.898 --> 02:30.567
Did I mention this book

02:30.650 --> 02:33.570
was written by a guy named
Robert Louis Stevenson?

02:33.653 --> 02:36.322
And published by the good
people at McGraw-Hill.

02:36.406 --> 02:38.074
So, in conclusion

02:38.158 --> 02:40.076
on the Simpson scale
of one to ten

02:40.160 --> 02:41.828
ten being the highest,
one being the lowest

02:41.911 --> 02:46.583
and five being average,
I give this book a nine.

02:46.666 --> 02:48.376
Ahem. Any questions?

02:48.459 --> 02:50.420
No? Then I'll just sit down.

02:50.503 --> 02:52.172
Bart, did you read the book?

02:52.255 --> 02:54.299
Mrs. Krabappel,
I am insulted.

02:54.382 --> 02:56.593
Is this a book report
or a witch hunt?

02:56.676 --> 03:00.847
Then perhaps you'd like to tell us
the name of the pirate.

03:00.930 --> 03:02.182
(thinking)
<i>Blackbeard, Captain Nemo,</i>

03:02.265 --> 03:03.349
<i>Captain Hook,</i>
<i>Long John Silver,</i>

03:03.433 --> 03:04.350
<i>Peg-Leg Pete, Bluebeard...</i>

03:04.434 --> 03:05.643
Bluebeard?

03:05.727 --> 03:07.270
Sit down, Bart.
I'll see you after class.

03:07.353 --> 03:09.606
Awww.

03:09.689 --> 03:11.357
Your grades have gotten
steadily worse

03:11.441 --> 03:12.650
since the beginning of
the term.

03:12.734 --> 03:14.861
-Are you aware of that?
-Yes, ma'am.

03:14.944 --> 03:16.321
Are you aware that there
is a major exam tomorrow

03:16.404 --> 03:18.907
-on colonial America?
-Yes, ma'am.

03:18.990 --> 03:21.326
Blah blah
blah blah blah...

03:21.409 --> 03:24.370
-Yes, ma'am.
-Blah blah blah blah blah blah...

03:24.454 --> 03:27.123
-Yes, ma'am.
-Bart, you haven't been paying attention

03:27.207 --> 03:28.666
-to a word I've said, have you?
-Yes, ma'am.

03:28.750 --> 03:30.001
-Well then, what did I say?
-Uh...

03:30.084 --> 03:33.004
Straighten up
and fly right?

03:33.087 --> 03:34.547
That was a lucky guess.

03:37.550 --> 03:39.219
Hyuh! Take that, granny!

03:39.302 --> 03:40.261
Oh, hide in the closet.

03:40.345 --> 03:42.096
Oh, no, deadly mothballs.

03:42.180 --> 03:43.723
Ew! Granny's kissing me.

03:43.806 --> 03:45.016
FEMALE VOICE:
<i>You have reached the level</i>

03:45.099 --> 03:46.809
<i>of ungrateful grandchild.</i>

03:46.893 --> 03:48.394
<i>Try again, if you dare.</i>

03:48.478 --> 03:49.979
<i>(granny giggling)</i>

03:50.063 --> 03:52.065
(evil laugh)

03:52.148 --> 03:54.651
Just a couple more games
and I'll hit the books.

03:56.694 --> 03:59.030
♪♪

04:04.410 --> 04:05.495
(laughing)

04:10.208 --> 04:11.751
(laughing)

04:11.834 --> 04:13.544
Soup's on!
Hurry up,

04:13.628 --> 04:15.380
or it will get that
icky skin on the top.

04:15.463 --> 04:17.340
Ew, I hate that
icky soup skin.

04:17.423 --> 04:20.635
Okay, right after dinner,
it's down to business.

04:20.718 --> 04:23.012
Hmm. Marge, could you get me
another beer, please?

04:23.096 --> 04:25.473
In a second, Homer.
Lisa has some good news.

04:25.556 --> 04:26.766
He doesn't care, Mom.

04:26.849 --> 04:28.101
Sure I do.

04:28.184 --> 04:29.727
I just want to have a beer
while I'm caring.

04:29.811 --> 04:31.437
-Marge?
-Homer!

04:31.521 --> 04:33.356
-(gasps)
-Go ahead, Lisa.

04:33.439 --> 04:34.732
Well, okay.

04:34.816 --> 04:36.693
I got an "A"
on my vocabulary test.

04:36.776 --> 04:39.112
(gasps) What?
You did?

04:39.195 --> 04:41.030
Well, that's just...

04:41.114 --> 04:43.199
Oh, what a glorious day!

04:43.283 --> 04:45.034
Lisa, hand me your paper.

04:45.118 --> 04:47.537
I'm just gonna take this
over to the refrigerator and--

04:47.620 --> 04:49.330
Hmm... well,
as long as I'm here

04:49.414 --> 04:51.207
I might as well kill
two birds with one stone.

04:51.291 --> 04:53.793
What's the big idea?
You covered up my paper.

04:53.876 --> 04:56.504
Heh-heh, look at those
funny little whiskers.

04:56.587 --> 04:57.964
Ooh! That reminds me.

04:58.047 --> 04:59.299
It's Big Gorilla Week
on Million Dollar Movie.

04:59.382 --> 05:00.675
Come on, boy.

05:00.758 --> 05:03.052
Uh, no, Dad.
I should really-- Hyuhh!

05:03.136 --> 05:06.055
Ooh, Gorilla the Conqueror--

05:06.139 --> 05:08.266
the granddaddy of them all.

05:08.349 --> 05:10.643
(crowd screaming)

05:10.727 --> 05:13.521
Oh, well,
maybe just one more hour.

05:13.604 --> 05:16.649
(Homer crying)

05:16.733 --> 05:17.859
It's so unfair.

05:17.942 --> 05:20.278
Just because he's different.

05:20.361 --> 05:22.488
Well, time
to hit the books.

05:22.572 --> 05:24.782
(chuckles) Burning the candle
at both ends, eh, boy?

05:24.866 --> 05:26.034
Go get 'em.

05:26.117 --> 05:27.577
All right, okay.

05:27.660 --> 05:30.121
Let's take care
of some business.

05:30.204 --> 05:32.749
"Chapter One--
A dream of freedom.

05:32.832 --> 05:37.003
"On September 15, 1620,
Puritan separatists

05:37.086 --> 05:40.590
"from the Church of England,
some living in Holland,

05:40.673 --> 05:42.967
"left Plymouth, England.

05:43.051 --> 05:45.720
(yawns)

05:45.803 --> 05:48.056
Their destination was..."

05:49.349 --> 05:51.476
Psst! Marge?

05:51.559 --> 05:53.561
Come take a look at this.

05:53.644 --> 05:57.398
Oh, the little tiger
tries so hard.

05:57.482 --> 05:59.317
Why does he
keep failing?

05:59.400 --> 06:01.694
Just a little dim,
I guess.

06:03.071 --> 06:04.822
MARGE: Bart, honey

06:04.906 --> 06:06.366
you're going
to miss your bus.

06:06.449 --> 06:07.909
Uh-oh.

06:07.992 --> 06:10.870
Hey, Bart dude!
Ooh, you look freaked.

06:10.953 --> 06:13.039
Hey, Otto man, I've got a big test
that I am not ready for.

06:13.122 --> 06:14.582
Could you please
crash the bus or something?

06:14.665 --> 06:17.919
Oh, sorry, little buddy.
Can't do it on purpose.

06:18.002 --> 06:19.712
But hey, maybe
you'll get lucky.

06:19.796 --> 06:21.297
Okay, no reason to panic.

06:21.381 --> 06:24.300
Find an egghead,
pump him for some answers,

06:24.384 --> 06:26.177
and boom! I'm back
on easy street.

06:27.970 --> 06:29.389
Oh-ho.

06:29.472 --> 06:31.808
Look at him.
I bet he didn't study again.

06:31.891 --> 06:34.811
And now he's gonna try to
kiss up and get answers from us.

06:34.894 --> 06:36.813
He's pathetic.

06:36.896 --> 06:38.272
Good morning, girls.

06:38.356 --> 06:39.649
BOTH: Good morning, Bart.

06:39.732 --> 06:42.985
Say, who's up
for a little cram session?

06:43.069 --> 06:46.364
I'll go first. What was the name
of the pilgrims' boat?

06:46.447 --> 06:48.408
The Spirit
of St. Louis.

06:48.491 --> 06:51.327
-And where'd they land?
-Sunny Acapulco.

06:51.411 --> 06:52.328
And why'd they
leave England?

06:52.412 --> 06:54.497
Giant rats.

06:54.580 --> 06:56.374
Cool! History's
coming alive.

06:56.457 --> 06:57.959
(girls giggling)

07:00.586 --> 07:02.046
As a natural enemy,

07:02.130 --> 07:03.673
I don't know
why I should care,

07:03.756 --> 07:05.466
but the information
pertaining to

07:05.550 --> 07:07.885
America's colonial period
that you've just received

07:07.969 --> 07:09.679
-is erroneous.
-So you're saying...

07:09.762 --> 07:12.014
A blindfolded chimp with
a pencil in his teeth

07:12.098 --> 07:14.350
has a better chance
of passing this test

07:14.434 --> 07:15.935
-than you do.
-(Bart groans)

07:16.018 --> 07:17.395
-(school bell rings)
-Thanks for the pep talk.

07:19.355 --> 07:22.066
All right students, take one
and pass the rest back.

07:22.150 --> 07:24.318
(thinking)
<i>Think, Simpson, think.</i>

07:24.402 --> 07:26.487
<i>Crisis brings out</i>
<i>the best in you.</i>

07:26.571 --> 07:28.322
(groaning)

07:28.406 --> 07:30.616
(scoffs)
What is it, Bart?

07:30.700 --> 07:31.659
Nothing.

07:31.742 --> 07:34.912
Must... take... test.

07:34.996 --> 07:36.372
Ooh!

07:36.456 --> 07:38.374
(groaning)

07:39.292 --> 07:41.210
(whistling)

07:44.672 --> 07:47.008
(groaning)

07:47.091 --> 07:48.926
What's the matter, son?

07:49.010 --> 07:52.221
Sharp, stabbing pains
in my stomach.

07:52.305 --> 07:54.682
Oh, dear.
I've heard of this.

07:54.765 --> 07:56.684
Do you feel a shooting pain
in your arm?

07:56.767 --> 07:58.394
-Both arms, ma'am.
-Mm-hmm.

07:58.478 --> 07:59.937
Temporary loss of vision?

08:00.021 --> 08:03.357
Who said that?
Come closer.

08:05.610 --> 08:07.069
-(bell ringing)
-Yes, dear?

08:07.153 --> 08:10.615
Ahh. Maybe, um,
one more dish.

08:10.698 --> 08:12.408
Make it double cappuccino
chocolate fudge.

08:12.492 --> 08:14.410
Ooh, your third bowl.

08:14.494 --> 08:15.870
I think you may be
on the mend.

08:15.953 --> 08:17.497
Is there anything else
I can get you?

08:17.580 --> 08:18.623
Hmm...

08:18.706 --> 08:20.541
Perhaps the TV?

08:20.625 --> 08:22.335
Of course. Homer!

08:22.418 --> 08:24.795
-What?
-Bring the television up.

08:24.879 --> 08:27.548
-Bart's got his vision back.
-D'oh!

08:27.632 --> 08:31.427
(straining) I wish I had
<i>amoria phlebitis.</i>

08:31.511 --> 08:33.304
Everyone knows
you're faking it, Bart.

08:33.387 --> 08:35.681
Well, everyone better
keep their mouth shut.

08:35.765 --> 08:37.850
You're gonna have to fail that
history test sooner or later.

08:37.934 --> 08:40.978
-I've got my bases covered.
-(phone line ringing)

08:41.062 --> 08:43.356
Hey, Milhouse, what'd
I miss in school today?

08:43.439 --> 08:46.275
Nothin' much. Lewis made Richard laugh
milk through his nose.

08:46.359 --> 08:48.528
Oh, you don't say. What about
that history test, huh?

08:48.611 --> 08:50.071
Piece of cake, huh?

08:50.154 --> 08:52.865
Listen, what did you get
for number one?

08:52.949 --> 08:54.742
Uh-huh.
Number two?

08:54.825 --> 08:57.161
Oh, yeah, that sounds right.

08:57.245 --> 08:58.454
Mm, mm-mm, mm, mm, mmm.

08:58.538 --> 09:00.039
Ahh!

09:00.122 --> 09:01.541
Here you go,
Mrs. Krabappel.

09:01.624 --> 09:04.544
I think you'll be
pleasantly surprised.

09:04.627 --> 09:08.839
Mm-hmm. Yep. Mm-hmm.

09:08.923 --> 09:11.551
This test is worse
than Milhouse's exam.

09:11.634 --> 09:13.469
Bart Simpson, I warned you.

09:13.553 --> 09:15.555
This is the final straw.

09:15.638 --> 09:19.141
Mr. And Mrs. Simpson, I think you know
our district psychiatrist

09:19.225 --> 09:21.894
-Dr. J. Loren Pryor.
-Hey, Doctor J.

09:21.978 --> 09:25.064
Hmph. I think what we have
on our hands here is a classic case

09:25.147 --> 09:28.901
of what laymen refer to
as "fear of failure."

09:28.985 --> 09:31.487
As a result,
Bart is an underachiever,

09:31.571 --> 09:35.449
and yet he seems to be--
how should I put this--

09:35.533 --> 09:38.035
-proud of it.
-Hmm.

09:38.119 --> 09:39.745
One of his problems may be
his short attention span

09:39.829 --> 09:41.414
which can lead to...

09:41.497 --> 09:43.708
blah blah blah
blah blah blah...

09:43.791 --> 09:45.626
-Uh-huh.
-Blah blah

09:45.710 --> 09:48.087
-blah blah blah blah...
-Hmm...

09:48.170 --> 09:51.507
Bart has failed his last
four exams in History.

09:51.591 --> 09:53.634
Is there anything
you're not telling us?

09:53.718 --> 09:54.719
No.

09:54.802 --> 09:55.970
Every other student
in the class has shown

09:56.053 --> 09:58.222
at least some form
of improvement,

09:58.306 --> 09:59.390
and yet you
continue to struggle.

09:59.473 --> 10:01.434
-Why is that?
-I don't know.

10:01.517 --> 10:03.060
Look at these results--

10:03.144 --> 10:05.396
Fifty-five,
Forty-two,

10:05.479 --> 10:07.648
Twenty-six--
A 12 on state capitals?

10:07.732 --> 10:11.235
Okay! Okay. Why are we dancing
around the obvious?

10:11.319 --> 10:13.946
I know it. You know it.
I am dumb, okay? Dumb as a post!

10:14.030 --> 10:15.406
You think I'm
happy about it?

10:15.489 --> 10:17.950
There, there, Bart,
you're just a late bloomer.

10:18.034 --> 10:19.910
Oh, I wish it were
that simple.

10:19.994 --> 10:22.455
As shameful and as emotionally
crippling as it may be,

10:22.538 --> 10:25.791
I'm afraid my recommendation
is for Bart Simpson to...

10:25.875 --> 10:27.627
repeat the fourth grade.

10:27.710 --> 10:30.713
What? You can't hold me back.
I'll do better. I promise.

10:30.796 --> 10:32.131
-Promises, promises.
-Oh, sure. That'll be the day.

10:32.214 --> 10:34.050
Well, maybe it
would help him

10:34.133 --> 10:35.801
to be left back.

10:35.885 --> 10:37.762
It won't be
so bad, Bart.

10:37.845 --> 10:39.555
No, I mean it.
You can't hold me back.

10:39.639 --> 10:41.349
I swear I'm gonna do better.

10:41.432 --> 10:43.100
Look at my eyes.
See the sincerity?

10:43.184 --> 10:45.227
See the conviction?
See the fear?

10:45.311 --> 10:49.065
As God is my witness,
I can pass the fourth grade!

10:49.148 --> 10:52.401
And if you don't, at least you'll
be bigger than the other kids.

10:52.485 --> 10:53.819
(concerned groan)

10:56.322 --> 10:59.617
Get off the bus, or forever
hold your peace, little dudes.

11:00.868 --> 11:02.662
Otto, you know
I respect you.

11:02.745 --> 11:04.497
I mean, you always
let us throw stuff at cars

11:04.580 --> 11:06.582
and try to tip the bus
on sharp turns.

11:06.666 --> 11:09.877
Damn thing never goes over,
does it?

11:09.960 --> 11:11.253
So what's in your head,
little man?

11:11.337 --> 11:14.757
Well, I been failing
a lot of tests recently.

11:14.840 --> 11:16.676
-Yuh-huh?
-And now they're talking about

11:16.759 --> 11:20.012
holding me back in the 4th grade
if I don't shape up.

11:20.096 --> 11:22.640
That's it?
Hey, relax, man.

11:22.723 --> 11:25.017
It could end up being the best thing
that ever happened to you.

11:25.101 --> 11:27.311
I got held back in
the fourth grade myself.

11:27.395 --> 11:29.271
Twice.

11:29.355 --> 11:33.150
And look at me, man.
Now I drive the school bus.

11:36.153 --> 11:37.863
DR. PRYOR:
<i>I'm afraid my recommendation</i>

11:37.947 --> 11:40.533
<i>is for Bart Simpson to</i>
<i>repeat the fourth grade...</i>

11:40.616 --> 11:44.078
(echoing) <i>repeat the fourth grade...</i>
<i>repeat the fourth grade...</i>

11:44.161 --> 11:47.707
All right, class.
The topic is world literature.

11:47.790 --> 11:51.752
What was the pirate's name
in "Treasure Island"?

11:51.836 --> 11:53.629
Bart Simpson?

11:53.713 --> 11:56.048
Look, lady,
I got a peptic ulcer,

11:56.132 --> 11:59.677
a wife hawking me for a new car,
and I need a root canal.

11:59.760 --> 12:02.012
Will you quit bugging me
about this stupid pirate?

12:02.096 --> 12:04.140
Psst.
It's Long John Silver, Dad.

12:04.223 --> 12:05.933
I heard that, Bart, Jr.

12:06.016 --> 12:09.019
I want to see both of you
after class today.

12:09.103 --> 12:12.690
D'oh!
Thanks a lot, son.

12:12.773 --> 12:14.567
(infield chatter)

12:16.360 --> 12:17.903
Yo, little help.

12:17.987 --> 12:19.780
I said, "little help."

12:19.864 --> 12:21.782
Throw me the ball,
Poindexter!

12:21.866 --> 12:23.784
Oh, I'm sorry, Bart.

12:23.868 --> 12:26.495
I'm unfamiliar with
the rules of your sport.

12:26.579 --> 12:29.498
I didn't want to interfere
with a ball in play.

12:29.582 --> 12:32.168
(laughing)

12:32.251 --> 12:35.504
Well, back to the forecastle
of the Pequod.

12:35.588 --> 12:37.882
-Hmm... hey, Martin?
-You have your ball.

12:37.965 --> 12:40.342
I have nothing else
of value.

12:40.426 --> 12:42.511
I need you to help me
get a passing grade.

12:42.595 --> 12:46.307
Well, you do need someone's
help to get a passing grade,

12:46.390 --> 12:48.726
but I don't know why
that someone should be me.

12:48.809 --> 12:49.810
Because I can make it
so the other kids

12:49.894 --> 12:51.520
don't laugh at you so much.

12:51.604 --> 12:54.982
They... laugh at me?

12:55.065 --> 12:58.569
I'd always considered myself
rather popular.

12:58.652 --> 13:01.155
You're not.
Watch. Hnh!

13:01.238 --> 13:03.157
(laughing)

13:03.240 --> 13:05.743
But my speed with numbers,

13:05.826 --> 13:08.913
my years of service
as a hall monitor,

13:08.996 --> 13:11.707
my prizewinning
dioramas--

13:11.791 --> 13:13.834
these things
mean nothing to them?

13:13.918 --> 13:15.711
Perhaps another
demonstration. Hnh!

13:15.795 --> 13:17.880
(kids laughing)

13:17.963 --> 13:20.549
Very well. You have made
your point, Bart.

13:20.633 --> 13:21.967
Then it's a deal?

13:22.051 --> 13:23.552
Yes.

13:23.636 --> 13:26.639
Alrighty, let's have a look-see
at your study area.

13:26.722 --> 13:28.307
-Study area?
-Yes,

13:28.390 --> 13:31.185
your sanctuary from
the hurly-burly of modern life.

13:31.268 --> 13:34.313
Well, there's a desk
under that junk over there.

13:34.396 --> 13:37.483
MARTIN: Oh, no, no, no, no.
This won't do at all.

13:37.566 --> 13:39.193
We're gonna have to
clean up this room,

13:39.276 --> 13:41.362
and we'll clearly need
a few ferns in here.

13:41.445 --> 13:43.948
No study area is complete
without adequate plant life.

13:46.075 --> 13:47.952
-No.
-No?

13:48.035 --> 13:49.578
Only geeks
sit in the front seat.

13:49.662 --> 13:51.413
From now on,
sit in the back row.

13:51.497 --> 13:53.457
And that's not just
on the bus.

13:53.541 --> 13:55.793
-It goes for school and church, too.
-Why?

13:55.876 --> 13:58.254
So no one can see
what you're doing.

13:58.337 --> 14:01.048
Oh! I think I understand.

14:01.131 --> 14:03.467
The potential for mischief
varies inversely

14:03.551 --> 14:05.803
with one's proximity
to the authority figure.

14:05.886 --> 14:08.597
Well, yeah, but don't
say it like that.

14:09.890 --> 14:11.308
(tires skidding)

14:13.394 --> 14:14.854
-(crashing)
-MARTIN: Ooh!

14:35.249 --> 14:36.208
Nnymm.

14:37.459 --> 14:39.003
Nyahh!

14:39.086 --> 14:40.004
Uhhnng!

14:40.087 --> 14:41.046
-Aaah!
-Aaah!

14:45.301 --> 14:47.344
Huh!

14:47.428 --> 14:50.598
Pretty soon you will be ready
to try it with a real book.

14:50.681 --> 14:53.601
(laughing)

14:53.684 --> 14:55.019
Who would have thought

14:55.102 --> 14:56.937
that pushing a boy into
the girls' lavatory

14:57.021 --> 14:58.439
could be such a thrill?

14:58.522 --> 15:00.816
The screams,
the humiliation,

15:00.900 --> 15:02.860
the fact that it wasn't me!

15:02.943 --> 15:04.653
I've never felt so alive.

15:04.737 --> 15:07.072
Great, Martin.
Now the big test is tomorrow,

15:07.156 --> 15:09.783
-and I haven't even started--
-Who cares about some test?

15:09.867 --> 15:11.702
Life's too short for tests!

15:11.785 --> 15:13.370
Hey, I thought we had a deal!

15:13.454 --> 15:14.955
Ha, ha, ha!

15:15.039 --> 15:18.042
The Martin Prince you made
a deal with no longer exists!

15:18.125 --> 15:20.502
Come on fellows,
to the arcade!

15:20.586 --> 15:21.629
Cool, Martin!

15:21.712 --> 15:23.255
All right, Martin!

15:23.339 --> 15:25.424
BOYS (chanting):
Martin! Martin! Martin!

15:25.507 --> 15:30.804
<i>♪♪ (humming</i>
<i>"Row, row, row your boat")</i>

15:30.888 --> 15:34.099
Bart?
It's past your bedtime.

15:34.183 --> 15:36.936
Okay.

15:37.019 --> 15:38.854
This is hopeless.

15:38.938 --> 15:41.982
Ohh...

15:42.066 --> 15:44.944
Well, old-timer, I guess
this is the end of the road.

15:45.027 --> 15:47.279
I know I haven't always
been a good kid

15:47.363 --> 15:50.240
but if I have to go
to school tomorrow,

15:50.324 --> 15:51.867
I'll fail the test
and be held back.

15:51.951 --> 15:54.745
I just need one more day
to study, Lord.

15:54.828 --> 15:56.246
I need your help.

15:56.330 --> 15:58.916
Prayer, the last refuge
of a scoundrel.

15:58.999 --> 16:02.753
A teacher's strike,
a power failure, a blizzard.

16:02.836 --> 16:04.588
Anything that will
cancel school tomorrow.

16:04.672 --> 16:06.632
I know it's asking a lot,

16:06.715 --> 16:09.718
but if anyone can do it,
you can.

16:09.802 --> 16:13.472
Thanking you in advance,
your pal, Bart Simpson.

16:19.520 --> 16:23.899
♪♪ ("The Hallelujah Chorus")

16:30.614 --> 16:32.950
(groaning)

16:33.033 --> 16:35.661
Wake up, Bart.
Rise and shine, little guy.

16:35.744 --> 16:37.121
Time to wake up.

16:37.204 --> 16:39.498
Oh, no, no.

16:39.581 --> 16:41.041
Wake up and
look at the snow.

16:41.125 --> 16:42.126
Huh?

16:42.209 --> 16:45.838
Whoa!
Good morning world!

16:45.921 --> 16:48.048
MAN (on radio): <i>Rise and shine,</i>
<i>Springfield residents.</i>

16:48.132 --> 16:50.384
<i>It's the Bill and</i>
<i>Marty Show. He's Bill.</i>

16:50.467 --> 16:51.885
<i>-He's Marty.</i>
<i>-Two grown men</i>

16:51.969 --> 16:53.637
<i>who can't get</i>
<i>enough of each other.</i>

16:53.721 --> 16:55.264
<i>BILL: And it looks like</i>
<i>we've got some snow-formation</i>

16:55.347 --> 16:56.849
<i>-for all those flake-lovers out there.</i>
-ALL: Shh!

16:56.932 --> 16:58.600
<i>-MARTY: Mm-hmm.</i>
<i>-BILL: Springfield electric,</i>

16:58.684 --> 17:00.853
<i>gas and water plants</i>
<i>are closed for the day.</i>

17:00.936 --> 17:02.354
<i>MARTY: Oh, now don't forget</i>
<i>the nuclear power plant, Bill.</i>

17:02.438 --> 17:04.023
-Please, please, please, please--
<i>-That's closed, too.</i>

17:04.106 --> 17:06.400
Whoo-hoo!
All right!

17:06.483 --> 17:08.694
<i>Now, for all you youngsters,</i>
<i>you toddlers,</i>

17:08.777 --> 17:10.195
<i>this is what</i>
<i>you've been waiting for.</i>

17:10.279 --> 17:12.948
<i>Springfield County</i>
<i>schools are--</i>

17:13.032 --> 17:14.950
<i>I can't read it.</i>
<i>I'm too excited.</i>

17:15.034 --> 17:17.202
<i>Uh-oh. Springfield County</i>
<i>schools will be...</i>

17:17.286 --> 17:18.454
-Please, please, please...
<i>-Closed!</i>

17:18.537 --> 17:21.999
-All right, man!
-Yeah! Woo-hoo-hoo!

17:22.082 --> 17:23.375
(children cheering)

17:23.459 --> 17:24.752
-Wait, come back--
-Your hat!

17:24.835 --> 17:27.963
-You're supposed to eat break--
-Wear your galoshes!

17:28.047 --> 17:29.631
Cowabunga!

17:29.715 --> 17:32.593
Remember to take a break
if your arms go numb.

17:32.676 --> 17:34.887
-Hey.
-I heard you last night, Bart.

17:34.970 --> 17:36.597
You prayed for this.

17:36.680 --> 17:38.766
Now your prayers
have been answered.

17:38.849 --> 17:40.059
I'm no theologian.

17:40.142 --> 17:42.269
I don't know who
or what God is, exactly.

17:42.352 --> 17:44.521
All I know is he's
a force more powerful

17:44.605 --> 17:45.856
than Mom and Dad
put together,

17:45.939 --> 17:47.691
-and you owe him big.
-(door slams)

17:47.775 --> 17:49.651
You're right.

17:49.735 --> 17:52.571
I asked for a miracle
and I got it.

17:52.654 --> 17:53.655
I got to study, man.

17:58.494 --> 18:01.080
I'm not missing anything.
Frozen earlobes.

18:01.163 --> 18:03.957
Trudging up that stupid sled
hill over and over again.

18:04.041 --> 18:05.542
How good could it be?

18:05.626 --> 18:09.171
(children cheering, laughing)

18:18.347 --> 18:20.015
(laughing)

18:20.099 --> 18:21.767
I haven't had
this much fun in years.

18:21.850 --> 18:24.520
-Aah!
-(laughs) Got you, Burnsie.

18:24.603 --> 18:27.022
(chuckles)
Why, you young ragamuffin.

18:27.106 --> 18:29.358
I was never one to back away
from a snowball fight.

18:29.441 --> 18:31.193
Smithers,
you may fire at will.

18:31.276 --> 18:32.194
Certainly, sir.

18:34.321 --> 18:35.781
♪♪

18:37.366 --> 18:41.662
I hereby declare this day
to be "Snow Day--

18:41.745 --> 18:44.123
The funnest day
in the history of Springfield."

18:44.206 --> 18:45.874
(cheering)

18:45.958 --> 18:49.878
<i>♪ Sleigh bells ring,</i>
<i>are you listening? ♪</i>

18:49.962 --> 18:53.465
<i>♪ In the lane,</i>
<i>snow is glistening ♪</i>

18:53.549 --> 18:57.052
<i>♪ A beautiful sight,</i>
<i>we're happy tonight ♪</i>

18:57.136 --> 19:00.514
<i>♪ Walking</i>
<i>in a winter wonderland ♪</i>

19:00.597 --> 19:03.767
<i>♪ Gone away</i>
<i>is the bluebird ♪</i>

19:03.851 --> 19:05.978
<i>♪ Here to stay... ♪</i>

19:08.647 --> 19:10.983
Got to study, got to study,
got to study!

19:14.820 --> 19:17.281
"Chapter Six--
Four Days in Philadelphia.

19:17.364 --> 19:18.782
"The first
Continental Congress

19:18.866 --> 19:20.284
"faced a difficult job.

19:20.367 --> 19:23.453
"Could the delegates agree
on recommendations

19:23.537 --> 19:24.913
that all Americans
could support?"

19:24.997 --> 19:28.125
We hold these truths
to be self-evident...

19:28.208 --> 19:31.503
<i>"We hold these truths</i>
<i>to be self-evident."</i>

19:31.587 --> 19:33.297
...that all men
are created equal.

19:33.380 --> 19:34.548
<i>"...that all men are</i>
<i>created equal."</i>

19:34.631 --> 19:36.091
That from that equal creation

19:36.175 --> 19:38.719
they derive rights,
inherent and inalienable--

19:38.802 --> 19:41.430
Hey, look everybody--
it's snowing!

19:41.513 --> 19:44.141
-In the middle of July?
-It's a miracle.

19:44.224 --> 19:47.686
Fellows, I've invented
something fun. The sled!

19:47.769 --> 19:50.564
(excited chatter)

19:50.647 --> 19:52.691
MAN:
Hey, look, everybody!

19:52.774 --> 19:55.485
John Hancock's
writing his name in the snow!

20:00.365 --> 20:01.783
Do you want to be
held back a grade?

20:01.867 --> 20:03.202
Concentrate, man!

20:04.620 --> 20:06.413
(slapping continues)

20:12.836 --> 20:14.254
Later, Mrs. K.

20:17.799 --> 20:19.718
Please turn in
your exam, Bart.

20:19.801 --> 20:22.137
Class is over.

20:22.221 --> 20:24.473
Do you think you could
grade it now, please?

20:24.556 --> 20:26.391
Well, all right.

20:26.475 --> 20:28.477
Let me get "old red."

20:29.603 --> 20:31.480
Mm-hmm.
Yup.

20:31.563 --> 20:33.565
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.

20:33.649 --> 20:37.069
Well, Bart, it's a 59.
That's another "F."

20:37.152 --> 20:39.821
Oh, no.
I can't believe it.

20:39.905 --> 20:42.324
I know, I know.
Another year together.

20:42.407 --> 20:45.327
Oh! It's going
to be hell.

20:46.536 --> 20:50.374
(sobbing)

20:50.457 --> 20:51.875
What's the matter?

20:51.959 --> 20:54.753
I would think you'd be
used to failing by now.

20:54.836 --> 20:56.755
No, you don't understand.

20:56.838 --> 20:59.841
I really tried this time.
I mean, I really tried.

20:59.925 --> 21:01.927
There, there.

21:02.010 --> 21:05.764
This is as good as I can do
and I still failed.

21:05.847 --> 21:08.934
Well, a 59--
it's a high "F."

21:09.017 --> 21:10.519
Who am I kidding?

21:10.602 --> 21:13.772
I really am a failure.
(sobbing)

21:13.855 --> 21:16.566
Oh! Now I know
how George Washington felt

21:16.650 --> 21:17.943
when he surrendered
Fort Necessity

21:18.026 --> 21:19.820
to the French in 1754.

21:19.903 --> 21:22.656
-What?
-Oh, you know, 1754,

21:22.739 --> 21:24.533
the famous defeat
to the French. (sobs)

21:24.616 --> 21:27.160
My God, Bart, you're right.

21:27.244 --> 21:28.537
-So?
-You just demonstrated

21:28.620 --> 21:31.248
applied knowledge,
and due to the difficulty

21:31.331 --> 21:32.958
and relative obscurity
of the reference,

21:33.041 --> 21:35.210
you deserve an extra point
on your exam.

21:35.294 --> 21:36.712
Hey, it's only fair.

21:36.795 --> 21:38.755
You mean, I passed?

21:38.839 --> 21:40.007
Just barely.

21:40.090 --> 21:41.550
(gasps)
I passed.

21:41.633 --> 21:42.718
I got a "D-".

21:42.801 --> 21:44.303
I passed!

21:44.386 --> 21:46.471
All right! Mwah!

21:46.555 --> 21:48.390
(singsongy) I passed, I passed,
I passed, I passed!

21:48.473 --> 21:51.018
I got a "D-"!
I passed!

21:51.101 --> 21:52.644
I got a "D-"! I passed!

21:52.728 --> 21:53.687
I got a "D-"!

21:53.770 --> 21:56.940
I passed!
I passed! I--

21:57.024 --> 21:59.276
Kissed the teacher!

22:05.324 --> 22:07.284
We're proud of you, boy.

22:07.367 --> 22:08.452
Thanks, Dad,

22:08.535 --> 22:10.954
but part of this "D-"
belongs to God.

22:13.790 --> 22:15.959
♪♪

22:59.795 --> 23:00.754
Shh!

23:04.049 --> 23:07.260
CAPTIONS ENHANCED BY
ROUNDABOUT ENTERTAINMENT INC.
